COMPONENT NAME: IKM Teradata Incremental Update
AUTHOR: Oracle
DESCRIPTION Integrates data into a Teradata target table in incremental update mode. Inexistent rows are inserted; already existing rows are updated. Data can be controlled. Invalid data is isolated in the Error Table and can be recycled. Comparison of data is made using the Update Key defined in the interface. It has to be set. The FLOW_CONTROL and STATIC_CONTROL options call the Check Knowledge Module to isolate invalid data (if no CKM is set, an error occurs). Both options must be set to NO in the case when an Integration Interface populates a TEMPORARY target datastore. By default flow table is created as MULTISET to allow duplicate rows in the flow table. The option FLOW_TABLE_OPTIONS is set by default to NO JOURNAL, NO FALLBACK to speed up batch processing.
REQUIREMENTS An update key has to be set in the interface.
BASIC CONFIGURATION Choose update key for target data store.
OPTIONS (Refer to Option descriptions for more information on each option) - INSERT: Execute insert command? - UPDATE: Execute update command? - COMMIT: Commit target transaction at the end of interface? - SYNC_JRN_DELETE:Remove deleted source rows from target ? - FLOW_CONTROL: Validate incoming data by a CKM? - RECYCLE_ERRORS: Recycle rejects from previous run? - STATIC_CONTROL: Validate data once loaded into target? - PRIMARY_INDEX: Specify primary index to be used on flow/ target table - DELETE_ALL: Delete all from target before loading? - VALIDATE: Validate KM options? - CREATE_TARG_TABLE: Create target table? - DELETE_TEMPORARY_OBJECTS: Drop ODI intermediate tables after load? - FLOW_TABLE_OPTIONS: DDL options for creating flow table - FLOW_TABLE_TYPE: Use set or multiset table for flow table? - COMPATIBLE: Use V12 merge command? - COLLECT_STATS: Collect statistics on flow and target table? - ODI_DDL: Specify, what DDL to be generated?
LIMITATIONS - When working with journalized data, if the "Synchronize deletions from journal" is executed, the deleted rows on the target are committed - Deletes are commited regardless of the COMMIT option - When Merge command is used, the selected update key needs to include PI of target table and partition columns - When Merge command is used (COMPATIBLE>=12), all row counters are set to zero, as no row count is reported back from TD - When COMMIT=NO, last drop flow statement issues warning, as table is still locked by pending transaction. - Temporary Indexes: HASH index may only be used on Teradata source tables with no identify column in PI definition (Teradata RDBMS restriction)
Automatically attempts to insert data into the Target Datastore of the Interface
Identifies and updates rows of the Target Datastore depending on the value of the UPDATE_KEY columns of the target datastore records.
Commit all data inserted or updated in the target datastore.
Check this option to synchronize journalized deletions. This option will take effect only if one source table is journalized in your interface.
Check this option if you wish to perform flow control.
Check this option to recycle data rejected by flow control in a previous execution of this interface.
Check this option to control the target table after having inserted or updated target data.

Specify primary index for flow table. Teradata uses the PI to spread data accross AMPs. It is important that the chosen PI has a high cardinality (many distint values) to ensure evenly spread data to allow maximum processing performance. Pleaes follow Teradata's recommandation on choosing a primary index, e.g. Teradata Database Design, Chapter "Primary Indexes" Valid options are [PK] Primary key of target table [UK] Update key set in interface <list of cols> This comma separated list of target columns defines the primary index. If no value is set (empty), no index will be created. NB: Teradata will automatically choose the first column of the table for the PI.
Check this option if you wish to delete all the rows of the target datastore.

This option generates an extra validation step during development. Validations performed are: - Validation of ODI_DLL option
This option should be turned off for all production use in particular for high-frequency execution. There is not added value in production, only processing overhead.
Check this option if you wish to create the target table.
Set this option to NO if you wish to retain temporary objects (tables, files and scripts) after integration. Useful for debugging.
no fallback, no before journal, no after journal
Additional options for the temporary I$ table. See documentation for valid values: - [NO] FALLBACK - [NO | DUAL] [BEFORE | AFTER] JOURNAL etc.

This option affects the way the data is merged into the target table:
Values Command 12 MERGE 6 INSERT, UPDATE
Note: Only Teradata V12 provides full ansi-compliant merge statement.
Collect stats on flow and target?
Collect statistics on primary index of flow and target table?

Specify handling of temporary tables with the following values: - DROP_CREATE: Always drop and recreate all temporary tables for every execution (default behaviour). - CREATE_DELETE_ALL: Create temporary tables when needed (usually for the first execution only) and use DELETE ALL to drop the temporary table content. Temporary table are reused for subsequent executions. - DELETE_ALL: Do not create temporary tables. Only submit DELETE ALL for all temporary tables. - NONE: Do not issue any DDL on temporary tables. Temporary tables should be handled separately.
